{"key":"processedPost-16333003","value":{"id":16333003,"first":16328051,"last":20056685,"when":1338861408,"utime":"06/05/12 04:56 AM","content":"I've yet to find a mushroom producing mycelium whether sclerotia producing or not which benefits in any way from colonization in total darkness.&nbsp; One book 30 years ago spouted that nonsense and people have been acting like Moses carried it off the mountain ever since. <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/shrug.gif\" alt=\":shrug:\" title=\":shrug:\"/><br /><br />Thanks for posting.&nbsp; Colonization and sclerotia production are somewhat faster in the presence of low level ambient light from day of inoculation.&nbsp; Don't use 24/7 light as it will slow down both.&nbsp; Just let your projects get normal ambient room light, but no direct sunlight or bright fluorescent light until the fruiting stage.<br />RR","title":"Re: GIVE YOUR TRUFFLES LIGHT - Your sclerotia species is in constant \"fruiting\"! *Pics*","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}